<div class="text">
<div class="header">Parsec</div>
<p><a href="parsec.html"><img align=right hspace=20 border=0
  src="images/parsec.gif" alt="Parsec logo"
  style="float: right; border: none; padding-left: 4pt"
  ></a>Parsec is a free monadic parser combinator library for
<a href="http://www.haskell.org">Haskell</a>.
Allthough combinator parsing is well known in literature, most libraries
are only implemented for personal use or
for small research examples. Parsec is designed from scratch as
an industrial-strength parser library.</p>

<p>It is simple, safe, well documented, has extensive libraries and good error messages.
It is also fast, doing thousands of lines per second on todays machines,
which might make it an acceptable alternative to bottom-up parser generators like <a href="http://www.haskell.org/happy">Happy</a>.
</p>
</div>

<div class="text">
<div class="header">Download</div>
<dl>
<dt>Parsec documentation <span class="quicklinks">[<a
   href="download/parsec/parsec.pdf">pdf</a>,
<a href="download/parsec/parsec.html">html</a>,
<a href="download/parsec/parsec.ps">ps</a>,
<a href="download/parsec/parsec-letter.pdf">pdf-letter</a>,
<a href="download/parsec/parsec-letter.ps">ps-letter</a>]</span></dt>
<dd>The user and reference guide for parsec. There is also a
<a href="pubs.html#parsec">technical report</a> describing
the inner workings of the library.

<p>The documentation is a bit outdated with regard to import statements.
Nowadays, Parsec is distributed with the standard Haskell libraries with
most Haskell compilers (<a href="http://www.haskell.org/ghc">GHC</a>,
<a href="http://www.haskell.org/nhc98">NHC</a>, <a href="http://www.haskell.org/hugs">Hugs</a>). You can import the Parsec library now
with hierarchical module names, for example:</p>
<pre>
import Text.ParserCombinators.Parsec
</pre>

</dd>
<dt>Parsec sources <span class="quicklinks">[<a
   href="download/parsec/parsec-2.0.zip">parsec-2.0.zip</a> (10 oct 2003)]</span></dt>
<dd><p>Packaged sources of Parsec. The latest sources are available from
<a href="http://cvs.haskell.org/cgi-bin/cvsweb.cgi/fptools/libraries/parsec">cvs</a>,
and this package is mainly for people that need easy access to the sources
and example parsers (like the Tiger parser).</p>
<p>There is also an old version of Parsec <span class="quicklinks">[<a
  href="download/parsec/parsec-1.1.zip">parsec-1.1.zip</a>]</span>
that does not use hierarchical module names.</p>
</dd>
</dl>

</div>

